<br>
It can be summed up in a few short and simple quotes (shamelessly yanked from the homepage of one Dave Krieger):<br>
1. Finite beings can never know absolute truth. <br>
2. A seeker of truth is willing to abandon beliefs when faced with contrary evidence. <br>
3. Faith is the desire not to know what is true. <br>
<br>
If you think these (particularly the last one) are horrible abominations, then read no further, because you will be disappointed. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
I believe people throw around the word &quot;faith&quot; without understanding what it really implies. I believe that when a person has faith in something, it is because they want so badly for it to be true that they are willing to sacrifice their rationality for it. I believe that just because a person, or even a million people, wish something to be so, does not make it so. I believe that my rationality is, ultimately, my most useful tool and that it should not be cast aside lightly. Faith is the desire to remain ignorant. The truth hurts, and faith is the bandage.<br>
<br>
Therefore, I choose not to accept ANYTHING based on &quot;faith.&quot;<br>
<br>
This means that, despite the fact that I was raised a Christian, despite the fact that I would like to think when family or friends pass away, they go to a &quot;better place,&quot; despite the fact that by and large the impact of Christianity on society is good, I choose not to accept it. Because it asks me to have &quot;faith,&quot; which means that it asks me to maintain an obviously false and totally inconsistent set of beliefs. This I refuse to do.<br>
<br>
The human soul? No, I don't think there's some mysterious force outside the body that has an impact on who we are. I think the human soul is merely a metaphor, a device to encapsulate all that we have yet to explain about humanity itself. In times of yore, people who mysteriously went catatonic at odd times, eyes glazed over and locked in a vapid stare, were said to have a disease &quot;of the soul.&quot; They were sent to priests instead of doctors, who performed elaborate exorcism rituals which, of course, did nothing. They couldn't explain it with the body, so they tacked it on to the soul. And this theory was accepted by most people at the time. <br>
<br>
Now we know, of course, that this disease is caused by late-stage progress of a certain type of rhinovirus. If you went to a medical convention and suggested that this disease be treated by treating &quot;the soul&quot; you would be laughed out of the room, and rightly so. The soul is becoming obsolete. Moreso by the day as we grow to understand just how the human body and mind perform their functions. There are just not many good reasons left to resort to some unseen entity beyond the body, except of course, because it feels good to think about it that way.<br>
<br>
What happens when you die? Unfortunately, all the evidence suggests that the computational machinery of your mind stops functioning. The thread on which your process was executing terminates. Done, fine, poof. As good as it would feel to think that I am moving on to something better, I'm afraid that just doesn't make it true. And that is my cynical view.<br>
<br>
With that said, if believing in any of these things really and genuinely makes your life better in even one small way, then <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  by all means</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> believe it, because the one thing we can all be sure of is that the time we are here is short, and we should make the best of it. <p><TABLE WIDTH=100% BORDER=0>
