<br>
Can we all assume for a minute that the human mind is capable of just about anything...hell, science and psychology prove all kinds of groovy new stuff all the time about what it can do, left to its own devices and whatever stimulus. Having said that...a few years ago I was a passenger in a truly nasty single-car accident - slammed head-on into a solid object at roughly 90 mph in a li'l '98 Cavalier. Around the moment of impact, I had my life flash before my eyes, in a manner of speaking. I dunno if this is what some people have spoken of, but that's the best definition I can attach to it; a series of still-frames of significant moments in my life flashed through my mind's eye. I can't recall everything that popped up, but I do recall that it was a *lot*, and it all happened in a small fraction of a second, as near as I can tell.<br>
<br>
So with that in mind, would it not be entirely safe to say that the concept of an eternal afterlife could be just that? Say, a dream-state that just seems to go on forever in the moment before death? Like, taking what happened to me in that accident and magnify it to the nth degree? Perhaps, under such circumstances, that particular dream state could easily be someone's heaven or, in the case of a nightmare, hell? Even further: those who have flatlined or had some other very-very-near-death experience (y'know, the white light, etc.) have merely been entering into that sort of eternal moment before the mind passes completely into nothingness (assuming, of course, that there's no real afterlife forthcoming). As I said, just a random thought, I felt it was worth posting. If not, let he who is without sin load the first hollow-point.<br>
<br>
